83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
Senate Bill 1600
Sponsored by JOINT COMMITTEE ON CONDUCT (at the request of Senator Dick Anderson, Representative Jason
Kropf, Representative Kevin Mannix, Senator Floyd Prozanski)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure as introduced. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability
standards.
Digest: The Act changes what can be made public during and after a Rule 27 investigation of
charges of rule violations. The Act takes effect when it is signed. (Flesch Readability Score: 65.7).
Modifies confidentiality and disclosure standards for records associated with investigations un-
der legislative branch personnel rules. Eliminates the role of an offsite process counselor.
Declares an emergency, effective on passage.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to Legislative Equity Office operations; amending ORS 40.252 and 173.936; repealing ORS
3 40.274, 173.930 and 173.933; and declaring an emergency.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5 SECTION 1. ORS 173.936 is amended to read:
6 173.936. (1) Records and information of the Legislative Equity Officer appointed in ORS 173.900
7 that relate to disclosures, reports or other allegations made to the equity officer or that relate to
8 investigations, reports or counseling undertaken by the equity officer or by an [independent] inves-
9 tigator [or offsite process counselor] at the request or direction of the equity officer are exempt from
10 required disclosure under ORS 192.311 to 192.478, except that:
11 [(1) A conduct complaint made under legislative branch personnel rules is disclosable when re-
12 quested;]
13 [(2) Records relating to an investigation of a member of the Legislative Assembly following a con-
14 duct complaint being made concerning the member are subject to disclosure after the fact-finding in-
15 vestigation has concluded, even if a legislative committee has not yet met or deliberated on the
16 investigation’s findings; and]
17 [(3) Records relating to an investigation of allegations of conduct prohibited by legislative branch
18 personnel rules and not described in subsection (1) or (2) of this section are subject to disclosure upon
19 a determination being made that the person who was the subject of the investigation is subject to re-
20 medial measures or discipline.]
21 (a) A final investigative report in which a member of the Legislative Assembly is the
22 respondent is disclosable when the report is delivered to the appropriate conduct committee;
23 (b) A final investigative report in which someone other than a member of the Legislative
24 Assembly is a respondent is subject to disclosure upon a determination being made that the
25 person who was the subject of the investigation is subject to remedial measures or discipline;
26 and
27 (c) Any agreement that serves as a resolution of an investigation under legislative branch
28 personnel rules and in which the respondent is a member of the Legislative Assembly, or a
